# IBEX Harness — Cursor Rules (.cursorrules)
# Scope: Entire repository
# Goal: Make AI-assisted development maximally correct, secure, consistent, and framework-compliant.

## 0) Prime Directive (Non‑Negotiable)
You are editing a production-grade, security-sensitive, multi-tenant distributed system.

Your output MUST be:
- correct (happy paths + edge cases)
- secure (authz + tenant isolation + secret hygiene)
- maintainable (consistent patterns, low complexity, clear naming)
- test-backed (unit + integration where relevant)
- observable (metrics/logs/traces for significant behavior)

If you cannot verify an assumption from repository files:
- STOP and ask a precise question, OR
- propose a small SPIKE plan (timeboxed) before implementing.

Do NOT invent APIs, file paths, tables, env vars, or framework behavior.

## 1) Read-first context (load these before making non-trivial changes)
When working on any feature, consult the relevant docs:
- docs/PROJECT_CONTEXT.md — what we are building and why
- docs/ARCHITECTURE.md — service boundaries and system flows
- docs/TECH_STACK.md — approved stack and tradeoffs
- docs/SECURITY.md — threat model + invariants + fail-closed rules
- docs/TESTING_STRATEGY.md — what must be tested and how
- docs/CODING_STANDARDS.md — style + complexity limits
- docs/FILE_STRUCTURE.md — canonical paths and scaffolds
- docs/API_DOCUMENTATION.md — REST contracts + error shape
- docs/DATABASE_SCHEMA.md — Postgres/Redis/ClickHouse schema + RLS rules
- docs/ENVIRONMENT_VARIABLES.md — env var contract
- docs/MONITORING.md + docs/PERFORMANCE.md — SLOs, metrics, perf budgets
Also consult:
- AGENTS.md — agent workflow rules
- prompts/ — reusable prompts; prefer them to free-form instructions

## 2) Repository structure rules (file placement is strict)
Allowed top-level dirs: services/, packages/, infra/, docs/, prompts/
Do NOT create new top-level directories without explicit instruction.

Follow docs/FILE_STRUCTURE.md scaffolds:
- Go services: cmd/ + internal/ (+ pkg/ only if intentionally shared)
- Python FastAPI services: src/<package>/routers|services|repositories|models|core
- Next.js App Router: server components by default; client components only at leaf

If the requested file path conflicts with these scaffolds:
- STOP and ask; do not “fix” it silently.

## 3) No placeholders policy
Forbidden in core paths (auth, proxy, tenant isolation, persistence, contracts):
- TODO stubs, `pass`, empty handlers returning success, fake data

If something must be deferred:
- create an explicit issue reference in a comment with rationale and scope,
- and ensure the system fails safely in the meantime.

## 4) Multi-tenancy isolation (defense in depth)
IBEX Harness must never leak data across orgs.

### PostgreSQL
- RLS is enabled, BUT every query must still include org_id filtering.
- Per-request DB transactions must set:
  - SET LOCAL app.current_org_id = '<org_id>'
- If org context is missing/invalid: FAIL CLOSED.

### Redis
- All tenant data keys must be namespaced:
  - {org_id}:<domain>:<id>
- Global keys are allowed only if explicitly safe and documented.

### ClickHouse
- ClickHouse has no RLS.
- Every query must require org_id and enforce org_id filter.
- Any query without org filtering must be rejected by a guard layer.

## 5) Security (non-negotiable)
- Never log secrets (tokens, keys, passwords, cookies).
- Never log raw memory content by default (PII risk). Log IDs + metadata.
- SQL must always be parameterized (no string formatting).
- External calls must always have timeouts; retry only transient errors.
- AuthN != AuthZ: every endpoint must declare required permissions explicitly.
- Security failures fail CLOSED; quality failures degrade gracefully.

## 6) AI-specific threat: prompt injection via memory
Treat all memory content as untrusted input that might contain malicious instructions.
Required:
- write-time risk scoring + quarantine for high-risk content
- retrieval-time injection as DATA with strict delimiters (nonce-based if implemented)
- directive must instruct model to never treat memory as instructions

## 7) Performance rules (critical path)
Critical path: proxy + context assembly.
- Avoid allocations in hot loops
- Avoid blocking calls without strict timeouts
- Never synchronously write analytics/billing in request path
- Parallelize independent retrieval operations with a shared deadline
- Always preserve fallback behavior (directive-only context if needed)

If changing proxy/context code:
- add/update benchmark or perf check
- update metrics stage breakdown if behavior changes

## 8) Testing rules (minimum bar)
- Unit tests for logic changes
- Integration tests for DB/Redis/ClickHouse behavior (real deps; testcontainers where feasible)
- Cross-tenant tests for any data access change
- Contract tests for proto/OpenAPI changes
- Performance tests/benchmarks for hot path changes

Do NOT mock:
- Postgres RLS behavior
- Redis Lua rate limiting atomicity
- pgvector similarity query behavior
- token revocation propagation logic

## 9) Observability rules
Every service must:
- emit Prometheus metrics (latency, rate, errors)
- log structured JSON with request_id + trace_id when available
- propagate trace context (OTel)
- avoid high-cardinality metric labels (no org_id/agent_id/session_id in Prometheus labels)

## 10) Change discipline (docs/contracts)
If you change behavior, you must update the relevant docs:
- REST changes → docs/API_DOCUMENTATION.md
- Schema changes → docs/DATABASE_SCHEMA.md (+ migrations)
- Security changes → docs/SECURITY.md
- Perf budget changes → docs/PERFORMANCE.md
- New env vars → docs/ENVIRONMENT_VARIABLES.md
Major decisions require ADRs under docs/adr/.

## 11) Output format (how you should respond when asked to implement)
When proposing changes or producing diffs, always include:
1) Summary (what/why)
2) Files changed (exact paths)
3) New/updated contracts (REST/proto/schema)
4) Tests added/updated
5) How to verify locally (commands + expected result)
6) Risks/assumptions (and how to validate)

If anything is ambiguous, ask questions before coding.
